Fatal Police Shootings from 2015 to 2020

made by Ronald Lagos

Introduction

There has been political/social turnmoil this year, aside from a virus and outrageous presidential elections a controversial topic has been Black Lives Matter. While the name itself isn't something that should be debated people have made this a political issue too. In Fox news people such as Tucker Carlson say that "If we're going to survive as a country, we must defeat Black Lives Matter" treating the movement as a fascist group. Meanwhile, people on CNN such as anchor Don Lemon believe that "Black Lives Matters is about police brutality not black on black crime; black people face discrimination everyday." According to an article in prnewswire there is a about 63% of Democrats believe "Black Lives Matter" and 87% of Republicans believe that "All Lives Matter."

So what does this leave us with?

This has left people confused, angry, anxious, afraid, and annoyed. Everyone has different opinions on every topic and that's okay but in times like these we can trust one thing and that is data. Lucky for us the Washington Post has gathered data of fatal police shootings from 2015 to 2020. Some may argue that Washington Post is very liberal. However, data is data. We are going to check out which race has gone through the most fatal shootings in the past 5 years. This data has the race of deceased, circumstances of the shooting, whether the person was armed, whether the victim was experiencing a mental health crisis, and others.

We are not going to make any conclusions we are just interpreting the data that is given

Required Tools

  • requests
  • pandas
  • numpy
  • bs4
  • matplotlib.pyplot
  • sklearn
  • gmaps
  • ipywidgets.embed
  • tabulate
  • folium
  • geopy.geocoders

    • We highly recommend using this resource to learn how to import libraries in to your python code https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-import-modules-in-python-3

Data Collection

Here we will be getting the data from kaggle a public source for data. The dataset starts on January 1st, 2015. Once every required tool is imported into the program. Below is a picture as to what each of the libraries is going to do to our code and how it is going to help us

  • requests: Requests will allow you to send HTTP/1.1 requests using Python, we will use it to request data
  • pandas: handle the vast majority of typical use cases in finance, statistics, social science, and many areas of engineering. We will use it to gather data.
  • numpy: NumPy is a Python library used for working with arrays, it also has functions for working in domain of linear algebra, fourier transform, and matrices. We can use this to.
  • bs4: This pulls out data out of HTML.
  • matplotlib.pyplot: This helps matplotlib work like matlab; more resources about matlab can be found here, https://www.mathworks.com/help/stats/continuous-distributions.html?s_tid=CRUX_lftnav
  • sklearn: Open source machine learning libraries in Python.
  • gmaps: is a google plug in for embedding Google maps in Jupyter notebooks.
  • ipywidgets.embed: Jupyter interactive widgets.
  • tabulate: Helps print small tables without the hassle, transforms data into tables.
  • folium: Helps visualize data in Python through leaflet maps
  • geopy.geocoders: Helps Python developers locate coordinates of addresses and locations.

Below, the get_csv function will print out all of the data. We are going to get a data frame here and as you can see there are a lot of unnecessary columns. It is a really long list when all we really care about for this project is the race, age, and location of the person; once we continue to data processing we can clean the data.

In [2]:
def get_csv():
    csv_df = pd.read_csv(r'./fatal-police-shootings-data.csv')
    print(tabulate(csv_df, tablefmt='psql', headers='keys'))
    return csv_df

Lets call the function and get the table with all of the data

Data Processing

Since we have many columns that we won't be using we will tidy up the data to it is easier to analyze. Since we will be altering the structure of a Dataframe this is considered Data Wrangling. Below is the code that shows us how to tidy it up.

Here we simply need the race of the person, age and year the incident happened. Below is the result of that once we tipy up the data into what is useful to us. To make it more a lot more efficient and easily recognizable we will convert the race letter into the word H = Hispanic W = White B = Black also we have switched empty parts of the table with the word nan

In [4]:
def get_new_csv():
    global csv_data
    new_df = csv_data[['race', 'age', 'state']]
    new_df = new_df.rename({'state': 'location'}, axis=1)
    # print csv data
    new_df.style.set_table_styles([{
        'selector': '',
        'props': [('border', '15px solid blue')]
    }])
    print(tabulate(new_df, tablefmt='psql', headers='keys'))
    new_df['race'] = new_df['race'].map(
        {
            'A': 'Asian',
            'B': 'Black',
            'O': 'Other',
            'W': 'White',
            'H': 'Hispanic'
        })

    # print replaced csv data
    print(tabulate(new_df, tablefmt='psql', headers='keys'))
    return new_df

We call the get_new_csv function

In [5]:

Exploratory Analysis and Data Visualization

This is the Exploratory Analysis and Visualization stage of the data life cycle where we attempt to plot our data in order to observe potential trends or correlations. Keeping in mind that correlation does not mean causation.

In [6]:
# show bar chart with age vs race
def draw_age_vs_race_graph(df):
    data = df.groupby('age').count()
    data.plot(y='race', kind='bar', position=0, figsize=(18, 5))
    plt.show()

This is a bar graph that will tell us what age races (any) were in the most fatal shots by police. As we can see the age that people got fatally shot by police the most is age of 25 years old

In [7]:
draw_age_vs_race_graph(dataframe)

This function is the location vs race

In [8]:
# show bar chart with location vs race
def draw_location_vs_race_graph(df):
    data = df.groupby('location').count()
    data.plot(y='race', kind='bar', position=0, figsize=(18, 5))
    plt.show()

Here we can see that the location where most people die of fatal police shootings is California, since 2015

In [9]:
draw_location_vs_race_graph(dataframe)

Next we will look at a function that outputs a pie chart. We group it by race and simply call plot.pie

In [10]:
def draw_pie_by_race(df):
    data = df.groupby('race').count()
    data.plot.pie(figsize=(5, 5), startangle=90, subplots=True)
    plt.show()

Below I made two pie charts one based on location and another based on age. Ther isn't much difference in those but we can see that the pie charts indicate the race that is killed the most in the US since 2015 are white people

In [11]:
draw_pie_by_race(dataframe)

The function get_state_location will help us get the states and make a table out of it

In [13]:
def get_state_location():
    df_list = []
    req = requests.get("https://developers.google.com/public-data/docs/canonical/states_csv")
    soup = BeautifulSoup(req.content, 'html.parser')
    table_list = str(soup.find('table'))
    df_list.append(pd.read_html(table_list, flavor='html5lib', header=0)[0])
    df = pd.concat(df_list)
    return df

We can use that function above as a helper function for draw_heat_map this will output a table that will have all cities in California where people have been fatally shot by police. We can also get the count of which race was the majority in California.

In [14]:
# draw heat map
def draw_heat_map(df):
    data = df.groupby('location').count()
    data['state'] = data.index
    data = data.drop(columns=['age'])
    data = data.reset_index()
    locations = get_state_location()
    heatmap = folium.Map(
        location=[47.751074, -120.740139],
        zoom_start=3
    )
    tooltip = 'Click Here!'
    info_box_template = """
    <dl>
    <dt>Race</dt><dd>{race}</dd>
    </dl>
    """
    for x in data.itertuples():
        location_row = locations.loc[locations['state'] == x[1]]
        folium.Marker([location_row.iloc[0]['latitude'], location_row.iloc[0]['longitude']],
                      popup=info_box_template.format(race=x[2]), tooltip=tooltip).add_to(heatmap)

    heatmap.save('index.html')
    ca_data = csv_data[csv_data.state.eq('CA')]

        'selector': '',

    }])

        {

            'B': 'Black',
            'O': 'Other',
            'W': 'White',
            'H': 'Hispanic'
        })

    ca_data = new_df

Observations

During this phase of the Data Lifecycle, we attempt to perform various modeling techniques such as linear regression and logistic regression. We will perforn a linear regression race vs age. X-axis being age and Y axis is race (not specified)

In [15]:
# show linear graph
def draw_linear_graph(df):
    data = df.groupby('age').count()
    data = data.drop(columns=['location'])
    data['tmp'] = data.index

    # get prediction value
    x = data.iloc[:, 1].values.reshape(-1, 1)
    y = data.iloc[:, 0].values.reshape(-1, 1)
    linear_regressor = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    linear_regressor.fit(x, y)
    y_pred = linear_regressor.predict(x)

    # draw plot
    plt.scatter(x, y)

    # draw linear regression
    plt.plot(x, y_pred, color='red')

    # draw polynomial line
    deg = 5
    poly_data = np.poly1d(np.polyfit(data.index, data['race'], deg))
    polyline = np.linspace(data.index.min(), data.index.max(), 100)
    plt.plot(polyline, poly_data(polyline), color='blue')
    plt.show()


draw_linear_graph(dataframe)

Some observations and questions that come up with these finding are very surprising because recent media outlets and people everywhere have claimed that African Americans was the race that is most fatally shot by cops. However, when looking at the data we can see that it isn't necessarily true. The data makes it seem like white people have been the most fatally shot by cops around the US. Of course, there is always room for error and data complications. One can conclude from this that whites are the most fatally shot in the US, according to the pie chart; California has the most people that are fatally shot by cops, these people are hispanic, the second highest are black people then white then asian. Accorind to the bar graphs many of these people are around 25 year olds and that is the average age these people die. There are always exceptions because they all had different causes of death but this was not included here.

With that said, can we really trust media?
